\begin_layout Standard
Developed by Fourier in 1822,
 the parabolic heat equation describes the diffusion process of physics quantities such as its namesake through a certain region:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{3} & \; & \frac{\partial}{\partial t}u & = & \; & \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x_{1}^{2}}u+\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x_{2}^{2}}u\\
\Longrightarrow &  & \dot{u} & = &  & \nabla^{2}u
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

The dataset is constructed with the same super-positioning technique as seen previously:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{i}\coloneqq\mathop{\sum_{k\in\left[1;c_{k}\right]}\biggl\{\texttt{R}^{k}\cdot u_{i}^{k}\biggr\}}\:,\quad\texttt{R}\in\mathbb{R}^{c_{k}}
\]

\end_inset

where each instance-sample 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}^{k}$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{i}^{k}\coloneqq\exp\left(-2k^{2}\pi^{2}t\right)\underbrace{\sin\left(k_{1}\pi x_{1}\right)\sin\left(k_{2}\pi x_{2}\right)}_{\eqqcolon\:\underline{\sin}}
\]

\end_inset

The validity of the construction is easily checked with the property of the squared sum of trig terms seen when defining the sum-of-sines dataset for the Poisson Equation in Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:poisson-sum-of-sines"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the uniformly zero spatial boundary-condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(t,\partial_{x_{1}},\partial_{x_{2}}\right)\coloneqq0
\]

\end_inset

one collects the details of this dataset as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{alignedat}{3} & \, & u_{i}^{k} & \coloneqq & \; & \exp\left(-2k^{2}\pi^{2}t\right)\cdot\mathop{\underline{\sin}}\\
 &  & u_{i}^{k}\left(0,\forall x_{1},\forall x_{2}\right) & \coloneqq &  & \mathop{\underline{\sin}}\quad\text{[Temporal Bound.]}\\
 &  & u_{i}^{k}\left(\forall t,\partial_{x_{1}},\partial_{x_{2}}\right) & \equiv &  & 0\qquad\text{[Spatial Bound.]}\\
 &  & \underline{\sin} & \coloneqq &  & \sin\left(k\pi x_{1}\right)\sin\left(k\pi x_{2}\right)
\end{alignedat}
\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

